# =============================================================================
# Where does .env live?
# =============================================================================
# On your PC, create a file named exactly:
#
#   c:\Users\chris\Desktop\pos-system\.env
#
# Same folder as: run.py, config.py, requirements.txt
#
# How: copy this file → rename the copy to ".env" (leading dot, no .example).
#      Or:  copy .env.example .env   (PowerShell, from the pos-system folder)
#
# .env is listed in .gitignore, so it will not be committed. Never put real
# secrets in .env.example (that file is often committed to Git).
# =============================================================================

# Flask environment: development | production
FLASK_CONFIG=development

# Secret key for sessions / signing (use a long random string in production)
SECRET_KEY=change-me

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DATABASE_URL — you use TWO different values (local PC vs Render hosting)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# You run Flask BOTH on your laptop AND on Render → use two places to set DB:
#
# 1) LOCAL (this .env file on your computer)
#    -----------------------------------------
#    In Render: open your PostgreSQL service → copy External Database URL.
#    Put it here as DATABASE_URL=...
#    Reason: your laptop is outside Render’s private network, so External works.
#    If connection fails, try adding:  ?sslmode=require  at the end of the URL.
#
# 2) RENDER (your Flask web service on Render — NOT this file)
#    ----------------------------------------------------------
#    Render does not read the .env file from your Git repo automatically.
#    In the dashboard: open your **Web Service** (Flask app) → Environment →
#    Environment Variables → add:
#      Key:   DATABASE_URL
#      Value: Internal Database URL from the **PostgreSQL** service page
#    Reason: the web app and DB are both on Render; Internal is faster and does
#    not require your DB to accept public connections.
#    Also set SECRET_KEY (and FLASK_CONFIG=production if you use that).
#
# Creating the database on Render:
#   Dashboard → New + → PostgreSQL → after it’s ready, open that DB service
#   and copy Internal vs External URLs as above.
#
# Local-only database (no Render): use OPTION B below instead.
#
# OPTION B — PostgreSQL only on your own machine
# -----------------------------------------------
# DATABASE_URL=postgresql://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/pos_db
#
# config.py rewrites postgres:// → postgresql:// if the host gives postgres://
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

DATABASE_URL=postgresql://USER:PASSWORD@HOST:5432/DATABASE_NAME
